Note:
F# Parser - Complete parsing for F# functional programming language

This file provides comprehensive parsing for the F# programming language,
building an Abstract Syntax Tree (AST) from token records produced by
fsharp_lexer. Tokens are 40-byte records (type, lexeme, value, line,
column); the parser stores token record pointers in AST value slots so
the HIR translator can recover identifier names and literal payloads via
the lexer's get_token_text/get_token_value/get_token_type accessors.

AST node layout (48 bytes, arena-allocated):
- node_type @0
- value @8        (token record pointer, or an operator token-type tag for
                   pipe nodes / the TOKEN_REC tag for recursive bindings)
- children @16    (List of child node pointers)
- child_count @24
- parent @32
- metadata @40    (optional type-annotation node for let bindings)

F# Features Parsed:
- Module declarations and namespace organization (dotted paths)
- Function definitions desugared to let + lambda
- Type definitions (records, discriminated unions, classes, interfaces)
- Pattern matching expressions with when guards
- Lambda expressions and the function-expression sugar
- Pipeline operators, function/operator application with precedence
- Exception handling (try/with/finally)
- Loops (while/do, for/in, for/=..to/downto)
- Collections (lists, arrays, records, tuples), quotations

Dependencies:
- fsharp_lexer.runa (token records, accessors, token type constants)
- compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa
- compiler/internal/string_utils.runa
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/fsharp/fsharp_lexer.runa" as Lexer
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/internal/string_utils.runa" as StringUtils

Note: ============================================================================
Note: F# AST Node Type Constants
Note: ============================================================================

Note: Program Structure
Constant AST_MODULE as Integer is 1001              Note: Module declaration
Constant AST_NAMESPACE as Integer is 1002           Note: Namespace declaration
Constant AST_OPEN as Integer is 1003                Note: Open statement
Constant AST_PROGRAM as Integer is 1004             Note: Root program node

Note: Type Declarations
Constant AST_TYPE_DECLARATION as Integer is 2001    Note: Type declaration
Constant AST_RECORD_TYPE as Integer is 2002         Note: Record type
Constant AST_UNION_TYPE as Integer is 2003          Note: Discriminated union
Constant AST_CLASS_TYPE as Integer is 2004          Note: Class type
Constant AST_INTERFACE_TYPE as Integer is 2005      Note: Interface type
Constant AST_STRUCT_TYPE as Integer is 2006         Note: Struct type
Constant AST_ENUM_TYPE as Integer is 2007           Note: Enum type
Constant AST_DELEGATE_TYPE as Integer is 2008       Note: Delegate type
Constant AST_TYPE_ABBREVIATION as Integer is 2009   Note: Type abbreviation

Note: Value and Function Declarations
Constant AST_LET_BINDING as Integer is 3001         Note: Let binding
Constant AST_FUNCTION_DEFINITION as Integer is 3002 Note: Function definition
Constant AST_VALUE_DECLARATION as Integer is 3003   Note: Value declaration
Constant AST_MEMBER_DECLARATION as Integer is 3004  Note: Member declaration
Constant AST_PROPERTY_DECLARATION as Integer is 3005 Note: Property declaration
Constant AST_METHOD_DECLARATION as Integer is 3006  Note: Method declaration
Constant AST_CONSTRUCTOR_DECLARATION as Integer is 3007 Note: Constructor

Note: Expressions
Constant AST_IDENTIFIER as Integer is 4001          Note: Variable/function name
Constant AST_LITERAL as Integer is 4002             Note: Literal value
Constant AST_APPLICATION as Integer is 4003         Note: Function application
Constant AST_LAMBDA as Integer is 4004              Note: Lambda expression (fun)
Constant AST_MATCH_EXPRESSION as Integer is 4005    Note: Match expression
Constant AST_IF_EXPRESSION as Integer is 4006       Note: If-then-else
Constant AST_LET_EXPRESSION as Integer is 4007      Note: Let expression
Constant AST_SEQUENCE_EXPRESSION as Integer is 4008 Note: Sequence expression
Constant AST_TRY_EXPRESSION as Integer is 4009      Note: Try-catch-finally
Constant AST_WHILE_EXPRESSION as Integer is 4010    Note: While loop
Constant AST_FOR_EXPRESSION as Integer is 4011      Note: For loop
Constant AST_COMPUTATION_EXPRESSION as Integer is 4012 Note: Computation expression
Constant AST_QUOTE_EXPRESSION as Integer is 4013    Note: Quotation expression
Constant AST_PIPE_EXPRESSION as Integer is 4014     Note: Pipeline expression
Constant AST_TUPLE_EXPRESSION as Integer is 4015    Note: Tuple literal
Constant AST_RECORD_EXPRESSION as Integer is 4016   Note: Record expression
Constant AST_LIST_EXPRESSION as Integer is 4017     Note: List literal
Constant AST_ARRAY_EXPRESSION as Integer is 4018    Note: Array literal
Constant AST_INTERPOLATED_STRING as Integer is 4019 Note: $"text {expr} text" interpolation

Note: Patterns
Constant AST_PATTERN_VARIABLE as Integer is 5001    Note: Variable pattern
Constant AST_PATTERN_LITERAL as Integer is 5002     Note: Literal pattern
Constant AST_PATTERN_WILDCARD as Integer is 5003    Note: Wildcard pattern (_)
Constant AST_PATTERN_AS as Integer is 5004          Note: As pattern (pattern as var)
Constant AST_PATTERN_OR as Integer is 5005          Note: Or pattern (pattern | pattern)
Constant AST_PATTERN_CONSTRUCTOR as Integer is 5006 Note: Constructor pattern
Constant AST_PATTERN_TUPLE as Integer is 5007       Note: Tuple pattern
Constant AST_PATTERN_LIST as Integer is 5008        Note: List pattern
Constant AST_PATTERN_ARRAY as Integer is 5009       Note: Array pattern
Constant AST_PATTERN_RECORD as Integer is 5010      Note: Record pattern
Constant AST_PATTERN_ACTIVE as Integer is 5011      Note: Active pattern
Constant AST_PATTERN_GUARD as Integer is 5012       Note: Pattern with guard (when)
Constant AST_PATTERN_TYPE_TEST as Integer is 5013   Note: :? Type dynamic type-test pattern

Note: Types
Constant AST_TYPE_NAME as Integer is 6001           Note: Type name
Constant AST_TYPE_VARIABLE as Integer is 6002       Note: Type variable ('a)
Constant AST_TYPE_APPLICATION as Integer is 6003    Note: Type application
Constant AST_TYPE_FUNCTION as Integer is 6004       Note: Function type (->)
Constant AST_TYPE_TUPLE as Integer is 6005          Note: Tuple type (* )
Constant AST_TYPE_LIST as Integer is 6006           Note: List type
Constant AST_TYPE_ARRAY as Integer is 6007          Note: Array type
Constant AST_TYPE_GENERIC as Integer is 6008        Note: Generic type
Constant AST_TYPE_CONSTRAINT as Integer is 6009     Note: Type constraint

Note: Object-Oriented Constructs
Constant AST_INHERIT as Integer is 7001             Note: Inherit declaration
Constant AST_INTERFACE_IMPLEMENTATION as Integer is 7002 Note: Interface implementation
Constant AST_OVERRIDE as Integer is 7003            Note: Override member
Constant AST_ABSTRACT_MEMBER as Integer is 7004     Note: Abstract member
Constant AST_DEFAULT_MEMBER as Integer is 7005      Note: Default member
Constant AST_STATIC_MEMBER as Integer is 7006       Note: Static member

Note: Special Constructs
Constant AST_UNIT as Integer is 8001                Note: Unit value ()
Constant AST_ATTRIBUTE as Integer is 8002           Note: Attribute annotation
Constant AST_MEASURE as Integer is 8003             Note: Unit of measure
Constant AST_ACTIVE_PATTERN_CASE as Integer is 8004 Note: Active pattern case

Note: ============================================================================
Note: F# Parser State and Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
F# parsing carries a position cursor over the token-record list plus a
cached current token so productions avoid a second list_get when only the
lookahead type is needed. The parser owns an arena so AST nodes can be
bulk-allocated; on the success path the arena's ownership transfers to
the AST consumer (the HIR translator reads the tree after the parser
record is gone), so only the error path destroys it.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
64-byte record laid out as: tokens @0 (List of token record pointers),
position @8, current_token @16 (cached token pointer), token_count @24,
error_message @32, has_error @40, indent_level @48, arena @56.
@End Implementation
Type called "FSharpParser":
    tokens as Integer           Note: List of token records from lexer
    position as Integer         Note: Current position in token list
    current_token as Integer    Note: Current token record pointer
    token_count as Integer      Note: Total number of tokens
    error_message as Integer    Note: Error message string
    has_error as Integer        Note: Error flag
    indent_level as Integer     Note: Current indentation level
    arena as Integer            Note: Memory arena for AST nodes
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parser Creation and Management
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Allocates the parser record, captures the token count once, pre-loads the
first token into the cache, and creates the AST arena. 1 MB arena
capacity: Layout arenas are mmap-backed with lazy page commit, so the
large initial size costs nothing physical while guaranteeing capacity for
a full parse run.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_fsharp_parser" takes token_list as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create F# parser instance

    Let parser_size be 64  Note: FSharpParser: 8 fields x 8 bytes
    Let parser be proc allocate from Layout with parser_size

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 0, token_list
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, 0   Note: position = 0

    Let count be proc list_length from List with token_list
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 24, count

    If count is greater than 0:
        Let first_token be proc list_get from List with token_list, 0
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, first_token

    Otherwise:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 32, 0  Note: error_message = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 40, 0  Note: has_error = false
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 48, 0  Note: indent_level = 0

    Let arena be proc arena_create from Layout with 1048576
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 56, arena

    Return parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
Error-path destructor: releases the AST arena (every node in O(1)) and
the parser record. The success path of parse_fsharp_source deliberately
does NOT call this - the arena owns the returned AST so it must outlive
the parser record there.
@End Reasoning
Process called "destroy_fsharp_parser" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Destroy F# parser and free resources including the AST arena

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let arena be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 56
    If arena is not equal to 0:
        proc arena_destroy from Layout with arena
    End If

    proc deallocate from Layout with parser
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Access and Navigation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Returns the cached current token record pointer. Cached because every
grammar production reads the lookahead at least once, often several
times in the same helper.
@End Reasoning
Process called "current_token" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get current token record pointer

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16
End Process

@Reasoning:
Type-level lookahead: the overwhelmingly common parser question is "what
KIND of token is next", so this composes the cache read with the lexer's
null-safe type accessor (null reads as TOKEN_EOF, giving uniform
end-of-input behavior at every call site).
@End Reasoning
Process called "current_token_type" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get the type tag of the current token (TOKEN_EOF past end)

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16
    Return proc get_token_type from Lexer with token
End Process

@Reasoning:
Multi-step lookahead used by productions that need to distinguish
ambiguous forms (e.g. `()` unit vs `(expr)` parenthesised expression, or
dotted-name continuation). Returns 0 when peeking past the end so the
type-level wrapper reads TOKEN_EOF there.
@End Reasoning
Process called "peek_token" takes parser as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Peek token record at offset from current position

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let token_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 24
    Let peek_pos be position plus offset

    If peek_pos is greater than or equal to token_count:
        Return 0  Note: EOF
    End If

    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 0
    Return proc list_get from List with tokens, peek_pos
End Process

Process called "peek_token_type" takes parser as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Peek the type tag at offset from current position (TOKEN_EOF past end)

    Let token be proc peek_token with parser, offset
    Return proc get_token_type from Lexer with token
End Process

@Reasoning:
Consumes one token by incrementing position and refreshing the cached
current_token slot. Setting the cache to 0 past EOF lets productions
terminate on TOKEN_EOF type tests rather than needing a separate at_eof
helper.
@End Reasoning
Process called "advance_token" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Advance to next token

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let token_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 24

    If position is greater than or equal to token_count:
        Return 0  Note: already at EOF
    End If

    Set position to position plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, position

    If position is less than token_count:
        Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 0
        Let next_token be proc list_get from List with tokens, position
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, next_token

    Otherwise:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, 0  Note: EOF
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Implements the "this token MUST be present" contract for mandatory
syntax (e.g. `then` after `if cond`). On mismatch sets the sticky error
flag and returns 0 so the caller can abort its production.
@End Reasoning
Process called "consume_token" takes parser as Integer, expected_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Consume a token of the expected type or report an error

    Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser

    If current_type is equal to expected_type:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return 1
    End If

    proc set_parse_error with parser, "Unexpected token"
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
F#'s offside rule treats newlines as soft statement boundaries; inside
multi-line constructs (after `=`, after `then`, between match arms) the
grammar permits any number of line breaks. The lexer emits TOKEN_NEWLINE
records so this helper drains them at exactly the production points
where line breaks are insignificant.
@End Reasoning
Process called "skip_newlines" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Advance past any run of newline tokens

    Let skipping be 1
    While skipping is equal to 1:
        Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_NEWLINE from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
        Otherwise:
            Set skipping to 0
        End If
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST Node Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Every AST node has the same fixed 48-byte layout and is arena-allocated
so creation is essentially a pointer bump. Zero-initializing every field
at construction means consumers can rely on 0 meaning "absent" for
value, children, parent, and metadata without extra null checks.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_ast_node" takes parser as Integer, node_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create AST node with specified type

    Let arena be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 56
    Let node_size be 48  Note: type + value + children + count + parent + metadata
    Let node be proc arena_allocate from Layout with arena, node_size

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 0, node_type  Note: node_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, 0         Note: value = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, 0        Note: children = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, 0        Note: child_count = 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 32, 0        Note: parent = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 40, 0        Note: metadata = null

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Children are stored in a canonical List (compiler/frontend/primitives/
collections/list.runa) created lazily on first add. The List grows
without bound so wide nodes (match expressions with many arms, modules
with many declarations) are handled correctly, and the HIR translator
reads children through the same list_get surface. child_count at offset
24 mirrors list_length so consumers can read the arity without a List
call.
@End Reasoning
Process called "add_child" takes parent as Integer, child as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Add child node to parent AST node

    If parent is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If child is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parent, 16
    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parent, 24

    If children is equal to 0:
        Set children to proc list_create from List
        If children is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parent, 16, children
    End If

    proc list_append from List with children, child

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with child, 32, parent
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parent, 24, child_count plus 1

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Null-safe value setter so productions that conditionally store a value
(token record pointers for identifiers/literals, operator tags for pipe
nodes) don't need to null-check first.
@End Reasoning
Process called "set_node_value" takes node as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Set value of AST node

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, value
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Error Handling
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Records the first parse error and sets a sticky flag so subsequent
productions can short-circuit. The first error is typically the most
useful so an existing message is not overwritten.
@End Reasoning
Process called "set_parse_error" takes parser as Integer, message as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Set parse error message

    Let existing be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 32
    If existing is equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 32, message
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 40, 1  Note: has_error = true
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "has_parse_error" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if parser has error

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 40
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Dotted Name Handling
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
F# qualified names (List.map, System.Collections, My.App namespace
paths) arrive from the lexer as alternating identifier and dot tokens.
Productions that treat the whole path as one name (identifiers in
expressions, open targets, namespace names, type references) call this
helper: it consumes the leading name token plus any .name continuations
and returns one token record whose lexeme is the joined dotted spelling.
When no dot follows, the original token is returned unchanged so the
common case allocates nothing.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_dotted_name_token" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Consume identifier (.identifier)* and return a single name token

    Let first be proc current_token with parser
    Let first_type be proc get_token_type from Lexer with first
    Let line be proc get_token_line from Lexer with first
    Let column be proc get_token_column from Lexer with first
    proc advance_token with parser

    Let name_text be proc get_token_text from Lexer with first
    Let saw_dot be 0

    Let joining be 1
    While joining is equal to 1:
        Let cur_type be proc current_token_type with parser
        If cur_type is not equal to TOKEN_DOT from Lexer:
            Set joining to 0
            Continue
        End If

        Let after_type be proc peek_token_type with parser, 1
        Let is_name be 0
        If after_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
            Set is_name to 1
        End If
        If after_type is equal to TOKEN_TYPE_NAME from Lexer:
            Set is_name to 1
        End If
        If is_name is equal to 0:
            Set joining to 0
            Continue
        End If

        proc advance_token with parser  Note: consume '.'
        Let part be proc current_token with parser
        Let part_text be proc get_token_text from Lexer with part
        proc advance_token with parser

        Let with_dot be proc string_concat from StringUtils with name_text, "."
        Set name_text to proc string_concat from StringUtils with with_dot, part_text
        Set saw_dot to 1
    End While

    If saw_dot is equal to 0:
        Return first
    End If

    Return proc create_token from Lexer with first_type, name_text, 0, line, column
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: F# Expression Parsing - Primaries
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Decides whether the current token can begin a primary expression. The
application layer (juxtaposition) iterates arguments exactly while this
predicate holds, which is what makes `f x y` consume x and y but stop
cleanly at keywords (`then`, `with`, `do`), operators, separators, and
closers without raising spurious errors.
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_primary_start" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check whether the current token can start a primary expression

    Let t be proc current_token_type with parser

    If t is equal to TOKEN_INTEGER from Lexer:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to TOKEN_FLOAT from Lexer:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to TOKEN_DECIMAL from Lexer:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to TOKEN_BIGINT from Lexer:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to TOKEN_BYTE from Lexer:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to TOKEN_STRING from Lexer:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to TOKEN_VERBATIM_STRING from Lexer:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to TOKEN_TRIPLE_QUOTE_STRING from Lexer:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to TOKEN_BYTE_STRING from Lexer:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to TOKEN_INTERP_STRING_START from Lexer:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to TOKEN_CHAR from Lexer:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to TOKEN_TRUE from Lexer:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to TOKEN_FALSE from Lexer:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to TOKEN_NULL from Lexer:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to TOKEN_TYPE_NAME from Lexer:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to TOKEN_UNDERSCORE from Lexer:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN from Lexer:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET from Lexer:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_ARRAY from Lexer:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE from Lexer:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_QUOTE from Lexer:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Primary expressions are the atomic building blocks: literals (every
numeric/string/char/bool/null kind the lexer produces), identifiers
(with dotted qualification), unit, parenthesised and tuple expressions,
collection literals, record expressions, and quotations. Literal and
identifier nodes store the token record pointer in the value slot - the
single contract the HIR translator's get_token_text/get_token_value
reads depend on.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_primary_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse primary expressions (literals, identifiers, parenthesized expressions)

    Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser
    Let token be proc current_token with parser

    Note: Literal kinds all share one shape: AST_LITERAL carrying the token
    Let is_literal be 0
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_INTEGER from Lexer:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_FLOAT from Lexer:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_DECIMAL from Lexer:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_BIGINT from Lexer:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_BYTE from Lexer:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_STRING from Lexer:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_VERBATIM_STRING from Lexer:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_TRIPLE_QUOTE_STRING from Lexer:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_BYTE_STRING from Lexer:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_CHAR from Lexer:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_TRUE from Lexer:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_FALSE from Lexer:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_NULL from Lexer:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If

    If is_literal is equal to 1:
        Let node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_LITERAL
        proc set_node_value with node, token
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return node
    End If

    Note: Unit value (), parenthesized expression, or tuple
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN from Lexer:
        Let next_type be proc peek_token_type with parser, 1
        If next_type is equal to TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN from Lexer:
            Set node to proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_UNIT
            proc advance_token with parser  Note: Skip (
            proc advance_token with parser  Note: Skip )
            Return node
        End If

        proc advance_token with parser  Note: Skip (
        proc skip_newlines with parser
        Let expr be proc parse_expression with parser
        proc skip_newlines with parser

        Note: Tuple expression (a, b, c)
        Let sep_type be proc current_token_type with parser
        If sep_type is equal to TOKEN_COMMA from Lexer:
            Let tuple_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_TUPLE_EXPRESSION
            proc add_child with tuple_node, expr

            Let collecting be 1
            While collecting is equal to 1:
                Set sep_type to proc current_token_type with parser
                If sep_type is equal to TOKEN_COMMA from Lexer:
                    proc advance_token with parser
                    proc skip_newlines with parser
                    Let element be proc parse_expression with parser
                    proc add_child with tuple_node, element
                    proc skip_newlines with parser
                Otherwise:
                    Set collecting to 0
                End If
            End While

            proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN from Lexer
            Return tuple_node
        End If

        proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN from Lexer
        Return expr
    End If

    Note: Identifiers (with dotted qualification) and constructor names
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
        Let name_token be proc parse_dotted_name_token with parser
        Set node to proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_IDENTIFIER
        proc set_node_value with node, name_token
        Return node
    End If

    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_TYPE_NAME from Lexer:
        Set name_token to proc parse_dotted_name_token with parser
        Set node to proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_IDENTIFIER
        proc set_node_value with node, name_token
        Return node
    End If

    Note: Wildcard _ in expression position (e.g. shorthand lambda bodies)
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_UNDERSCORE from Lexer:
        Set node to proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_PATTERN_WILDCARD
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return node
    End If

    Note: List literal [1; 2; 3]
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_list_expression with parser
    End If

    Note: Array literal [|1; 2; 3|]
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_ARRAY from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_array_expression with parser
    End If

    Note: Record literal {field = value}
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_record_expression with parser
    End If

    Note: Quotation literal <@ expr @>
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_QUOTE from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_quotation_expression with parser
    End If

    Note: Interpolated string $"text {expr} text"
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_INTERP_STRING_START from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_interpolated_string with parser
    End If

    proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected expression"
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Interpolated strings arrive from the lexer as a START segment token,
then ordinary expression tokens for each hole, then a MID segment token
per hole closure. Each segment token's numeric payload is the
continuation flag (1 = an expression hole follows, 0 = string complete).
The AST shape is one AST_INTERPOLATED_STRING node whose children
alternate literal segments and hole expressions: child 0 is always an
AST_LITERAL carrying the START token, then [expression, AST_LITERAL]
pairs follow for every hole - so the HIR translator can walk children in
order and distinguish text from expressions by node kind. Empty text
segments are preserved (an AST_LITERAL whose token lexeme is the empty
string) so segment positions stay aligned with hole positions.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_interpolated_string" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse interpolated string into alternating literal/expression children

    Let node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_INTERPOLATED_STRING

    Let segment_token be proc current_token with parser
    Let segment_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_LITERAL
    proc set_node_value with segment_node, segment_token
    proc add_child with node, segment_node

    Let has_hole be proc get_token_value from Lexer with segment_token
    proc advance_token with parser

    While has_hole is equal to 1:
        Let hole_expr be proc parse_expression with parser
        If hole_expr is equal to 0:
            proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected expression in string interpolation hole"
            Return 0
        End If
        proc add_child with node, hole_expr

        Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser
        If current_type is not equal to TOKEN_INTERP_STRING_MID from Lexer:
            proc set_parse_error with parser, "Unterminated string interpolation"
            Return 0
        End If

        Set segment_token to proc current_token with parser
        Set segment_node to proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_LITERAL
        proc set_node_value with segment_node, segment_token
        proc add_child with node, segment_node

        Set has_hole to proc get_token_value from Lexer with segment_token
        proc advance_token with parser
    End While

    Return node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: F# Expression Parsing - Application and Operator Precedence
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Builds an AST_APPLICATION node for a binary operator use: the callee is
an AST_IDENTIFIER whose value is the operator's token record (so the
HIR translator recovers the operator spelling via get_token_text), and
the operands are the remaining children. Representing operators as
applications matches F# semantics exactly - every infix operator is a
function - and lets the single translate_application path in the HIR
translator handle arithmetic without a dedicated binary-expression
AST kind.
@End Reasoning
Process called "make_operator_application" takes parser as Integer, op_token as Integer, left as Integer, right as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Build operator application node: (op left right)

    Let op_ident be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_IDENTIFIER
    proc set_node_value with op_ident, op_token

    Let app_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_APPLICATION
    proc add_child with app_node, op_ident
    proc add_child with app_node, left
    proc add_child with app_node, right

    Return app_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Application sits between primary expressions and the operator
precedence ladder. Juxtaposition is the tightest-binding form after
member access, so this layer iterates greedily over primaries exactly
while is_primary_start holds. Building application nodes one argument
at a time keeps the tree left-associative without recursion.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_application_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse function application with proper left-associativity

    Let expr be proc parse_primary_expression with parser
    If expr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let applying be 1
    While applying is equal to 1:
        Let can_apply be proc is_primary_start with parser
        If can_apply is equal to 0:
            Set applying to 0
            Continue
        End If

        Let arg be proc parse_primary_expression with parser
        If arg is equal to 0:
            Set applying to 0
            Continue
        End If

        Let app_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_APPLICATION
        proc add_child with app_node, expr
        proc add_child with app_node, arg
        Set expr to app_node
    End While

    Return expr
End Process

@Reasoning:
Unary layer: prefix minus (negation), `not`, and `!` (ref dereference)
bind looser than application (`-f x` is -(f x) in F#) but tighter than
every infix operator. Each prefix form becomes a one-argument operator
application so the HIR sees a uniform call shape.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_unary_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse unary expressions (-x, not x, !r)

    Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser

    Let is_unary be 0
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_MINUS from Lexer:
        Set is_unary to 1
    End If
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_NOT from Lexer:
        Set is_unary to 1
    End If
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_DEREF from Lexer:
        Set is_unary to 1
    End If

    If is_unary is equal to 1:
        Let op_token be proc current_token with parser
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let operand be proc parse_unary_expression with parser

        Let op_ident be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_IDENTIFIER
        proc set_node_value with op_ident, op_token

        Let app_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_APPLICATION
        proc add_child with app_node, op_ident
        proc add_child with app_node, operand
        Return app_node
    End If

    Return proc parse_application_expression with parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
Exponentiation ** is right-associative in F# (2.0 ** 3.0 ** 2.0 is
2^(3^2)), achieved by recursing into this same level for the right
operand.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_power_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse ** exponentiation (right-associative)

    Let left be proc parse_unary_expression with parser

    Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_POWER from Lexer:
        Let op_token be proc current_token with parser
        proc advance_token with parser
        proc skip_newlines with parser
        Let right be proc parse_power_expression with parser
        Return proc make_operator_application with parser, op_token, left, right
    End If

    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Multiplicative level: * / % left-associative over the power level.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_multiplicative_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse * / % (left-associative)

    Let expr be proc parse_power_expression with parser

    Let looping be 1
    While looping is equal to 1:
        Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser
        Let is_op be 0
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_MULTIPLY from Lexer:
            Set is_op to 1
        End If
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_DIVIDE from Lexer:
            Set is_op to 1
        End If
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_MODULO from Lexer:
            Set is_op to 1
        End If

        If is_op is equal to 0:
            Set looping to 0
            Continue
        End If

        Let op_token be proc current_token with parser
        proc advance_token with parser
        proc skip_newlines with parser
        Let right be proc parse_power_expression with parser
        Set expr to proc make_operator_application with parser, op_token, expr, right
    End While

    Return expr
End Process

@Reasoning:
Additive level: + and - left-associative over the multiplicative level.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_additive_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse + and - (left-associative)

    Let expr be proc parse_multiplicative_expression with parser

    Let looping be 1
    While looping is equal to 1:
        Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser
        Let is_op be 0
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_PLUS from Lexer:
            Set is_op to 1
        End If
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_MINUS from Lexer:
            Set is_op to 1
        End If

        If is_op is equal to 0:
            Set looping to 0
            Continue
        End If

        Let op_token be proc current_token with parser
        proc advance_token with parser
        proc skip_newlines with parser
        Let right be proc parse_multiplicative_expression with parser
        Set expr to proc make_operator_application with parser, op_token, expr, right
    End While

    Return expr
End Process

@Reasoning:
Range level: a .. b builds a range application. F# uses ranges in list
comprehensions and for loops; representing them as an application of
the ".." operator keeps the call-shaped uniformity.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_range_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse a .. b range expressions

    Let expr be proc parse_additive_expression with parser

    Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_RANGE from Lexer:
        Let op_token be proc current_token with parser
        proc advance_token with parser
        proc skip_newlines with parser
        Let right be proc parse_additive_expression with parser
        Return proc make_operator_application with parser, op_token, expr, right
    End If

    Return expr
End Process

@Reasoning:
Cons :: is right-associative (1 :: 2 :: [] is 1 :: (2 :: [])), achieved
by recursing into this same level for the right operand.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_cons_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse :: cons (right-associative)

    Let left be proc parse_range_expression with parser

    Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_DOUBLE_COLON from Lexer:
        Let op_token be proc current_token with parser
        proc advance_token with parser
        proc skip_newlines with parser
        Let right be proc parse_cons_expression with parser
        Return proc make_operator_application with parser, op_token, left, right
    End If

    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Comparison level: = <> < > <= >= over the cons level. F# comparisons
are non-chaining in idiomatic use; a left-associative loop accepts the
rare chained form without a dedicated diagnostic.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_comparison_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse comparison operators (left-associative)

    Let expr be proc parse_cons_expression with parser

    Let looping be 1
    While looping is equal to 1:
        Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser
        Let is_op be 0
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_EQUAL from Lexer:
            Set is_op to 1
        End If
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_NOT_EQUAL from Lexer:
            Set is_op to 1
        End If
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_LESS_THAN from Lexer:
            Set is_op to 1
        End If
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_GREATER_THAN from Lexer:
            Set is_op to 1
        End If
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_LESS_EQUAL from Lexer:
            Set is_op to 1
        End If
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_GREATER_EQUAL from Lexer:
            Set is_op to 1
        End If

        If is_op is equal to 0:
            Set looping to 0
            Continue
        End If

        Let op_token be proc current_token with parser
        proc advance_token with parser
        proc skip_newlines with parser
        Let right be proc parse_cons_expression with parser
        Set expr to proc make_operator_application with parser, op_token, expr, right
    End While

    Return expr
End Process

@Reasoning:
Logical levels: && binds tighter than ||, both left-associative, both
looser than comparisons - matching F# operator precedence.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_logical_and_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse && (left-associative)

    Let expr be proc parse_comparison_expression with parser

    Let looping be 1
    While looping is equal to 1:
        Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser
        If current_type is not equal to TOKEN_AND_OP from Lexer:
            Set looping to 0
            Continue
        End If

        Let op_token be proc current_token with parser
        proc advance_token with parser
        proc skip_newlines with parser
        Let right be proc parse_comparison_expression with parser
        Set expr to proc make_operator_application with parser, op_token, expr, right
    End While

    Return expr
End Process

Process called "parse_logical_or_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse || (left-associative)

    Let expr be proc parse_logical_and_expression with parser

    Let looping be 1
    While looping is equal to 1:
        Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser
        If current_type is not equal to TOKEN_OR_OP from Lexer:
            Set looping to 0
            Continue
        End If

        Let op_token be proc current_token with parser
        proc advance_token with parser
        proc skip_newlines with parser
        Let right be proc parse_logical_and_expression with parser
        Set expr to proc make_operator_application with parser, op_token, expr, right
    End While

    Return expr
End Process

@Reasoning:
The pipeline layer is the loosest precedence level. Both pipeline forms
(forward |> and backward <|) are exposed as AST_PIPE_EXPRESSION nodes
with the operator's token TYPE TAG stored in the node value slot - the
HIR translator compares that slot directly against TOKEN_PIPE_RIGHT /
TOKEN_PIPE_LEFT to choose the call rewrite. |> accumulates left-
associatively (loop) while <| right-associates (recursion), matching
the F# spec.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_pipeline_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse pipeline expressions with |> and <| operators

    Let expr be proc parse_logical_or_expression with parser

    Let looping be 1
    While looping is equal to 1:
        Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser

        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_PIPE_RIGHT from Lexer:  Note: |>
            proc advance_token with parser
            proc skip_newlines with parser
            Let right_expr be proc parse_logical_or_expression with parser

            Let pipe_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_PIPE_EXPRESSION
            proc add_child with pipe_node, expr
            proc add_child with pipe_node, right_expr
            proc set_node_value with pipe_node, TOKEN_PIPE_RIGHT from Lexer

            Set expr to pipe_node

        Otherwise:
            If current_type is equal to TOKEN_PIPE_LEFT from Lexer:  Note: <|
                proc advance_token with parser
                proc skip_newlines with parser
                Set right_expr to proc parse_pipeline_expression with parser

                Set pipe_node to proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_PIPE_EXPRESSION
                proc add_child with pipe_node, expr
                proc add_child with pipe_node, right_expr
                proc set_node_value with pipe_node, TOKEN_PIPE_LEFT from Lexer

                Set expr to pipe_node

            Otherwise:
                Set looping to 0
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return expr
End Process

@Reasoning:
Top-level expression dispatcher. Keyword-led expressions (`fun`, `let`,
`match`, `if`, `try`, `while`, `for`, `function`) each have their own
production; everything else falls through to the precedence ladder via
parse_pipeline_expression. None of the keywords overlap so a flat
sequence is correct.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse general F# expression

    Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser

    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_FUN from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_lambda_expression with parser
    End If

    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_LET from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_let_expression with parser
    End If

    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_MATCH from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_match_expression with parser
    End If

    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_IF from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_if_expression with parser
    End If

    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_TRY from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_try_expression with parser
    End If

    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_WHILE from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_while_expression with parser
    End If

    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_FOR from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_for_expression with parser
    End If

    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_FUNCTION from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_function_expression with parser
    End If

    Return proc parse_pipeline_expression with parser
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: F# Pattern Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
F# patterns appear in three positions (match arms, fun parameters, let
bindings) and share one grammar: wildcards, variables (with optional
`as` aliases), literals, tuples, lists, arrays, records, and
constructor applications (both parenthesised `Cons(h, t)` and
juxtaposed `Some x`). Dispatching through one entry point keeps the
recursive cases self-routing. Variable/literal/constructor patterns
store their token record in the value slot per the HIR contract.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_pattern" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse F# patterns for match expressions and function parameters

    Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser
    Let token be proc current_token with parser

    Note: Wildcard pattern _
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_UNDERSCORE from Lexer:
        Let node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_PATTERN_WILDCARD
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return node
    End If

    Note: Dynamic type-test pattern :? TypeName [as binder]. The type name
    Note: token (dotted paths joined) lands in the value slot; the optional
    Note: as-binder becomes an AST_PATTERN_VARIABLE child so the catch-clause
    Note: translator reads [type name, bound variable] from one node.
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_TYPE_TEST from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser  Note: Skip :?

        Let name_type be proc current_token_type with parser
        Let is_type_name be 0
        If name_type is equal to TOKEN_TYPE_NAME from Lexer:
            Set is_type_name to 1
        End If
        If name_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
            Set is_type_name to 1
        End If
        If is_type_name is equal to 0:
            proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected type name after :?"
            Return 0
        End If

        Let type_token be proc parse_dotted_name_token with parser
        Set node to proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_PATTERN_TYPE_TEST
        proc set_node_value with node, type_token

        Let after_type be proc current_token_type with parser
        If after_type is equal to TOKEN_AS from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser  Note: Skip 'as'
            Let binder_type be proc current_token_type with parser
            If binder_type is not equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
                proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected identifier after 'as' in type-test pattern"
                Return 0
            End If
            Let binder_token be proc current_token with parser
            Let binder_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_PATTERN_VARIABLE
            proc set_node_value with binder_node, binder_token
            proc add_child with node, binder_node
            proc advance_token with parser
        End If

        Return node
    End If

    Note: Variable pattern (with optional as-alias)
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
        Set node to proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_PATTERN_VARIABLE
        proc set_node_value with node, token
        proc advance_token with parser

        Let next_type be proc current_token_type with parser
        If next_type is equal to TOKEN_AS from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser  Note: Skip 'as'
            Let var_type be proc current_token_type with parser
            If var_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
                Let var_token be proc current_token with parser
                Let as_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_PATTERN_AS
                proc add_child with as_node, node

                Let var_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_PATTERN_VARIABLE
                proc set_node_value with var_node, var_token
                proc add_child with as_node, var_node

                proc advance_token with parser
                Return as_node
            End If
        End If

        Return node
    End If

    Note: Literal patterns
    Let is_literal be 0
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_INTEGER from Lexer:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_FLOAT from Lexer:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_STRING from Lexer:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_CHAR from Lexer:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_TRUE from Lexer:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_FALSE from Lexer:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_NULL from Lexer:
        Set is_literal to 1
    End If

    If is_literal is equal to 1:
        Set node to proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_PATTERN_LITERAL
        proc set_node_value with node, token
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return node
    End If

    Note: Tuple pattern (x, y, z) or parenthesised pattern (p) or unit ()
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN from Lexer:
        Set next_type to proc peek_token_type with parser, 1
        If next_type is equal to TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN from Lexer:
            Note: Unit pattern () binds nothing
            Set node to proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_PATTERN_WILDCARD
            proc advance_token with parser
            proc advance_token with parser
            Return node
        End If

        proc advance_token with parser  Note: Skip (

        Let first_pattern be proc parse_pattern with parser

        Note: Optional type annotation (x: type) - parsed and attached as metadata
        Let anno_type be proc current_token_type with parser
        If anno_type is equal to TOKEN_COLON from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Let anno be proc parse_type_expression with parser
            If first_pattern is not equal to 0:
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with first_pattern, 40, anno
            End If
        End If

        Let sep_type be proc current_token_type with parser
        If sep_type is equal to TOKEN_COMMA from Lexer:
            Let tuple_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_PATTERN_TUPLE
            proc add_child with tuple_node, first_pattern

            Let collecting be 1
            While collecting is equal to 1:
                Set sep_type to proc current_token_type with parser
                If sep_type is equal to TOKEN_COMMA from Lexer:
                    proc advance_token with parser  Note: Skip ,
                    Let pattern be proc parse_pattern with parser
                    proc add_child with tuple_node, pattern
                Otherwise:
                    Set collecting to 0
                End If
            End While

            proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN from Lexer
            Return tuple_node
        End If

        proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN from Lexer
        Return first_pattern
    End If

    Note: List pattern [x; y; z] or []
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_list_pattern with parser
    End If

    Note: Array pattern [|x; y; z|]
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_ARRAY from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_array_pattern with parser
    End If

    Note: Record pattern {field = pattern}
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_record_pattern with parser
    End If

    Note: Constructor pattern: Name, Name(p1, p2), or juxtaposed Name p
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_TYPE_NAME from Lexer:
        Set node to proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_PATTERN_CONSTRUCTOR
        proc set_node_value with node, token
        proc advance_token with parser

        Set next_type to proc current_token_type with parser
        If next_type is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser  Note: Skip (

            Let arg_loop be 1
            While arg_loop is equal to 1:
                Let arg_pattern be proc parse_pattern with parser
                proc add_child with node, arg_pattern

                Set sep_type to proc current_token_type with parser
                If sep_type is equal to TOKEN_COMMA from Lexer:
                    proc advance_token with parser  Note: Skip ,
                Otherwise:
                    Set arg_loop to 0
                End If
            End While

            proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN from Lexer
            Return node
        End If

        Note: Juxtaposed single argument: Some x, Cons _, Ok 1
        Let arg_kind be 0
        If next_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
            Set arg_kind to 1
        End If
        If next_type is equal to TOKEN_UNDERSCORE from Lexer:
            Set arg_kind to 1
        End If
        If next_type is equal to TOKEN_INTEGER from Lexer:
            Set arg_kind to 1
        End If
        If next_type is equal to TOKEN_STRING from Lexer:
            Set arg_kind to 1
        End If
        If next_type is equal to TOKEN_TRUE from Lexer:
            Set arg_kind to 1
        End If
        If next_type is equal to TOKEN_FALSE from Lexer:
            Set arg_kind to 1
        End If

        If arg_kind is equal to 1:
            Let juxta_arg be proc parse_pattern with parser
            proc add_child with node, juxta_arg
        End If

        Return node
    End If

    proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected pattern"
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
F# match arms allow or-pattern alternatives (`| A | B -> body`) and a
`when` guard expression after the pattern. A pipe between a pattern and
its arrow is unambiguously an or-alternative (an arm separator can only
appear after an arm body), so the alternatives loop consumes pipes
greedily here. Alternatives collect as the children of one
AST_PATTERN_OR node; a guard then wraps whichever pattern shape resulted
(`A | B when g` parses as (A|B) guarded by g, matching F# precedence)
into an AST_PATTERN_GUARD node so the consumer always sees one piece per
case regardless of guard presence.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_pattern_with_guard" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse pattern with optional or-alternatives and when guard

    Let pattern be proc parse_pattern with parser
    If pattern is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: A pattern inside an arm is always followed by ->, when, or an
    Note: or-alternative pipe, so line breaks here are insignificant and
    Note: skipping them enables the idiomatic cross-line alternative layout.
    proc skip_newlines with parser

    Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_PIPE from Lexer:
        Let or_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_PATTERN_OR
        proc add_child with or_node, pattern

        Let collecting be 1
        While collecting is equal to 1:
            Set current_type to proc current_token_type with parser
            If current_type is equal to TOKEN_PIPE from Lexer:
                proc advance_token with parser  Note: Skip |
                proc skip_newlines with parser
                Let alternative be proc parse_pattern with parser
                If alternative is equal to 0:
                    Return 0
                End If
                proc add_child with or_node, alternative
                proc skip_newlines with parser
            Otherwise:
                Set collecting to 0
            End If
        End While

        Set pattern to or_node
    End If

    Set current_type to proc current_token_type with parser
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_WHEN from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser  Note: Skip 'when'

        Let guard_expr be proc parse_pipeline_expression with parser

        Let guard_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_PATTERN_GUARD
        proc add_child with guard_node, pattern
        proc add_child with guard_node, guard_expr

        Return guard_node
    End If

    Return pattern
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: F# Specific Expression Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
F# lambdas use `fun p1 p2 ... -> body` with one or more parameters,
each parsed as a pattern (so destructuring lambdas like
`fun (x, y) -> x + y` work). The body comes after `->` and is a single
expression. Body is distinguished from parameters by position: always
the last child.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_lambda_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse lambda expression (fun parameters -> body)

    proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_FUN from Lexer

    Let lambda_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_LAMBDA

    Let collecting be 1
    While collecting is equal to 1:
        Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_ARROW from Lexer:
            Set collecting to 0
            Continue
        End If
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
            Set collecting to 0
            Continue
        End If

        Let param be proc parse_pattern with parser
        If param is equal to 0:
            Set collecting to 0
            Continue
        End If
        proc add_child with lambda_node, param
    End While

    proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_ARROW from Lexer
    proc skip_newlines with parser

    Let body be proc parse_expression with parser
    proc add_child with lambda_node, body

    Return lambda_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
`match expr with | p1 -> e1 | p2 -> e2 ...` is encoded as an
AST_MATCH_EXPRESSION whose first child is the scrutinee and remaining
children are case nodes (each an AST_PATTERN_GUARD holding the pattern
and its arm expression). Reusing AST_PATTERN_GUARD as the case
container is intentional: it already carries the pattern + expression
pair. Newlines between arms are insignificant per the offside rule, so
the arm loop skips them before testing for the next |.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_match_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse match expression (match expr with cases)

    proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_MATCH from Lexer

    Let match_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_MATCH_EXPRESSION

    Let expr be proc parse_pipeline_expression with parser
    proc add_child with match_node, expr

    proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_WITH from Lexer
    proc skip_newlines with parser

    Let parsing_cases be 1
    While parsing_cases is equal to 1:
        Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_PIPE from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser  Note: Skip |
        End If

        Let pattern be proc parse_pattern_with_guard with parser
        If pattern is equal to 0:
            Set parsing_cases to 0
            Continue
        End If

        Let arrow_ok be proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_ARROW from Lexer
        If arrow_ok is equal to 0:
            Set parsing_cases to 0
            Continue
        End If
        proc skip_newlines with parser

        Let result_expr be proc parse_expression with parser

        Let case_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_PATTERN_GUARD
        proc add_child with case_node, pattern
        proc add_child with case_node, result_expr

        proc add_child with match_node, case_node

        Note: Look across line breaks for the next | arm
        proc skip_newlines with parser
        Set current_type to proc current_token_type with parser
        If current_type is not equal to TOKEN_PIPE from Lexer:
            Set parsing_cases to 0
        End If
    End While

    Return match_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
F# `if/then/elif/else` is an expression so every branch produces a
value. The AST stores condition, then-branch, then the optional
else-branch (or the nested elif-if) as children. elif recurses into
the shared tail parser so arbitrarily long chains nest as
right-leaning if nodes.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_if_tail" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse the condition/then/else portion of an if expression (after if/elif)

    Let if_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_IF_EXPRESSION

    Let condition be proc parse_pipeline_expression with parser
    proc add_child with if_node, condition

    proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_THEN from Lexer
    proc skip_newlines with parser

    Let then_expr be proc parse_expression with parser
    proc add_child with if_node, then_expr

    proc skip_newlines with parser
    Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser

    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_ELSE from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        proc skip_newlines with parser
        Let else_expr be proc parse_expression with parser
        proc add_child with if_node, else_expr
        Return if_node
    End If

    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_ELIF from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let elif_expr be proc parse_if_tail with parser
        proc add_child with if_node, elif_expr
        Return if_node
    End If

    Return if_node
End Process

Process called "parse_if_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse if-then-elif-else expression

    proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_IF from Lexer
    Return proc parse_if_tail with parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
F# let-expressions combine one primary binding with zero or more
sibling bindings (each introduced by `and`), and optionally an
`in expr` clause. The `and` chain supports mutually recursive
definitions; the trailing `in` makes the construct an expression with
a body value.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_let_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse let expression (let bindings in expr)

    proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_LET from Lexer

    Let let_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_LET_EXPRESSION

    Let binding be proc parse_let_binding with parser
    proc add_child with let_node, binding

    Let chaining be 1
    While chaining is equal to 1:
        Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_AND from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Let and_binding be proc parse_let_binding with parser
            proc add_child with let_node, and_binding
        Otherwise:
            Set chaining to 0
        End If
    End While

    Let tail_type be proc current_token_type with parser
    If tail_type is equal to TOKEN_IN from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        proc skip_newlines with parser
        Let in_expr be proc parse_expression with parser
        proc add_child with let_node, in_expr
    End If

    Return let_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
F# `try ... with | pat -> ... finally ...` supports both exception
handling (via `with` arms, like match) and an optional `finally`
cleanup block. The AST stores the try body first, then one
AST_PATTERN_GUARD child per handler arm, then optionally the finally
expression as the last (non-guard) child - the HIR translator
distinguishes handler arms from the finally expression by node type.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_try_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse try-with-finally expression

    proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_TRY from Lexer
    proc skip_newlines with parser

    Let try_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_TRY_EXPRESSION

    Let try_body be proc parse_expression with parser
    proc add_child with try_node, try_body

    proc skip_newlines with parser
    Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser

    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_WITH from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        proc skip_newlines with parser

        Let parsing_handlers be 1
        While parsing_handlers is equal to 1:
            Set current_type to proc current_token_type with parser
            If current_type is equal to TOKEN_PIPE from Lexer:
                proc advance_token with parser
            End If

            Let pattern be proc parse_pattern_with_guard with parser
            If pattern is equal to 0:
                Set parsing_handlers to 0
                Continue
            End If

            Let arrow_ok be proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_ARROW from Lexer
            If arrow_ok is equal to 0:
                Set parsing_handlers to 0
                Continue
            End If
            proc skip_newlines with parser

            Let handler_expr be proc parse_expression with parser

            Let catch_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_PATTERN_GUARD
            proc add_child with catch_node, pattern
            proc add_child with catch_node, handler_expr
            proc add_child with try_node, catch_node

            proc skip_newlines with parser
            Set current_type to proc current_token_type with parser
            If current_type is not equal to TOKEN_PIPE from Lexer:
                Set parsing_handlers to 0
            End If
        End While
    End If

    proc skip_newlines with parser
    Set current_type to proc current_token_type with parser
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_FINALLY from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        proc skip_newlines with parser
        Let finally_expr be proc parse_expression with parser
        proc add_child with try_node, finally_expr
    End If

    Return try_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
F# while-loops: `while cond do body [done]`. Modern F# light syntax
omits `done`, so it is consumed when present and not required.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_while_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse while expression (while condition do body)

    proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_WHILE from Lexer

    Let while_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_WHILE_EXPRESSION

    Let condition be proc parse_pipeline_expression with parser
    proc add_child with while_node, condition

    proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_DO from Lexer
    proc skip_newlines with parser

    Let body be proc parse_expression with parser
    proc add_child with while_node, body

    proc skip_newlines with parser
    Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_DONE from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Return while_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
F# has two for forms: `for x in iterable do body` and
`for i = start to|downto finish do body`. Both produce the same
3-child AST shape (variable, iterable, body) that the HIR translator
expects; the counted form synthesises its iterable as a `..` range
application so downstream code sees one iteration protocol. `done` is
optional as with while.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_for_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse for expression (for var in expr do body / for var = a to b do body)

    proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_FOR from Lexer

    Let for_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_FOR_EXPRESSION

    Let var_type be proc current_token_type with parser
    If var_type is not equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected variable name"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let var_token be proc current_token with parser
    Let var_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_IDENTIFIER
    proc set_node_value with var_node, var_token
    proc add_child with for_node, var_node
    proc advance_token with parser

    Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser

    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_EQUAL from Lexer:
        Note: Counted form: for i = start to/downto finish do body
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let start_expr be proc parse_pipeline_expression with parser

        Let dir_type be proc current_token_type with parser
        Let dir_ok be 0
        If dir_type is equal to TOKEN_TO from Lexer:
            Set dir_ok to 1
        End If
        If dir_type is equal to TOKEN_DOWNTO from Lexer:
            Set dir_ok to 1
        End If
        If dir_ok is equal to 0:
            proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected 'to' or 'downto'"
            Return 0
        End If

        Note: Synthesise the range operator token carrying the loop direction
        Let dir_token be proc current_token with parser
        Let dir_line be proc get_token_line from Lexer with dir_token
        Let dir_col be proc get_token_column from Lexer with dir_token
        Let range_text be ".."
        If dir_type is equal to TOKEN_DOWNTO from Lexer:
            Set range_text to "..-"
        End If
        Let range_token be proc create_token from Lexer with TOKEN_RANGE from Lexer, range_text, 0, dir_line, dir_col
        proc advance_token with parser

        Let finish_expr be proc parse_pipeline_expression with parser

        Let iterable be proc make_operator_application with parser, range_token, start_expr, finish_expr
        proc add_child with for_node, iterable

    Otherwise:
        proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_IN from Lexer
        Let iter_expr be proc parse_pipeline_expression with parser
        proc add_child with for_node, iter_expr
    End If

    proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_DO from Lexer
    proc skip_newlines with parser

    Let body be proc parse_expression with parser
    proc add_child with for_node, body

    proc skip_newlines with parser
    Set current_type to proc current_token_type with parser
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_DONE from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Return for_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
F# `function p1 -> e1 | p2 -> e2` is sugar for
`fun x -> match x with ...`. The parser materialises this as an
AST_LAMBDA whose children are pattern-guarded case nodes - the same
shape match expressions use - because downstream lowering recognises
that shape uniformly.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_function_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse function expression (function pattern -> expr | ...)

    proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_FUNCTION from Lexer
    proc skip_newlines with parser

    Let function_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_LAMBDA

    Let parsing_cases be 1
    While parsing_cases is equal to 1:
        Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_PIPE from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
        End If

        Let pattern be proc parse_pattern_with_guard with parser
        If pattern is equal to 0:
            Set parsing_cases to 0
            Continue
        End If

        Let arrow_ok be proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_ARROW from Lexer
        If arrow_ok is equal to 0:
            Set parsing_cases to 0
            Continue
        End If
        proc skip_newlines with parser

        Let expr be proc parse_expression with parser

        Let case_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_PATTERN_GUARD
        proc add_child with case_node, pattern
        proc add_child with case_node, expr
        proc add_child with function_node, case_node

        proc skip_newlines with parser
        Set current_type to proc current_token_type with parser
        If current_type is not equal to TOKEN_PIPE from Lexer:
            Set parsing_cases to 0
        End If
    End While

    Return function_node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Collection Literal Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
F# list literals use `[e1; e2; e3]` with semicolons (and newlines as
soft separators). The empty case `[]` is handled by detecting the
closing bracket immediately after the opener.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_list_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse list literal [1; 2; 3]

    proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET from Lexer
    proc skip_newlines with parser

    Let list_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_LIST_EXPRESSION

    Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACKET from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return list_node
    End If

    Let collecting be 1
    While collecting is equal to 1:
        Let element be proc parse_expression with parser
        If element is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        proc add_child with list_node, element

        proc skip_newlines with parser
        Set current_type to proc current_token_type with parser
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_SEMICOLON from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            proc skip_newlines with parser
            Continue
        End If
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACKET from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Set collecting to 0
            Continue
        End If

        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected ';' or ']'"
        Return 0
    End While

    Return list_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
F# array literals use `[|e1; e2|]` with dedicated multi-character
delimiter tokens, so they are distinguishable from list literals at
the lexer level. Same element loop as lists with the array closer.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_array_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse array literal [|1; 2; 3|]

    proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_LEFT_ARRAY from Lexer
    proc skip_newlines with parser

    Let array_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_ARRAY_EXPRESSION

    Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_RIGHT_ARRAY from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return array_node
    End If

    Let collecting be 1
    While collecting is equal to 1:
        Let element be proc parse_expression with parser
        If element is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        proc add_child with array_node, element

        proc skip_newlines with parser
        Set current_type to proc current_token_type with parser
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_SEMICOLON from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            proc skip_newlines with parser
            Continue
        End If
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_RIGHT_ARRAY from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Set collecting to 0
            Continue
        End If

        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected ';' or '|]'"
        Return 0
    End While

    Return array_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Record literals use `{field = value; field = value}` syntax. Each field
becomes an AST_LET_BINDING child of the record node whose value slot
holds the field-name TOKEN and whose single child is the field value
expression - the exact contract translate_field_assignment in the HIR
translator reads. Field names must be identifier tokens.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_record_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse record expression {field = value; ...}

    proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE from Lexer
    proc skip_newlines with parser

    Let record_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_RECORD_EXPRESSION

    Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return record_node
    End If

    Let collecting be 1
    While collecting is equal to 1:
        Let field_type be proc current_token_type with parser
        If field_type is not equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
            proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected field name"
            Return 0
        End If
        Let field_token be proc current_token with parser
        proc advance_token with parser

        Let eq_ok be proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_EQUAL from Lexer
        If eq_ok is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        proc skip_newlines with parser

        Let field_value be proc parse_expression with parser

        Let field_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_LET_BINDING
        proc set_node_value with field_node, field_token
        proc add_child with field_node, field_value
        proc add_child with record_node, field_node

        proc skip_newlines with parser
        Set current_type to proc current_token_type with parser
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_SEMICOLON from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            proc skip_newlines with parser
            Continue
        End If
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Set collecting to 0
            Continue
        End If

        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected ';' or '}'"
        Return 0
    End While

    Return record_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
F# code quotations `<@ expr @>` capture an expression as a typed AST
value at runtime. The inner expression is parsed normally; the
quotation wraps it in a distinct AST kind so semantic analysis can
lift the contained tree to a runtime representation.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_quotation_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse quotation expression <@ expr @>

    proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_LEFT_QUOTE from Lexer

    Let quote_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_QUOTE_EXPRESSION

    Let quoted_expr be proc parse_expression with parser
    proc add_child with quote_node, quoted_expr

    proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_QUOTE from Lexer

    Return quote_node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: F# Type Expression Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Type expressions cover named types (int, string, MyType, dotted
System.String paths, and 'a type variables, which lex as identifiers
with an apostrophe lexeme), generic instantiations in both F# forms -
prefix List<int> / Option<int> / Dictionary<K, V> angle-bracket
applications and postfix int option / int list juxtaposed applications -
plus right-associative function arrows (int -> int -> bool). Name atoms
become AST_TYPE_NAME nodes carrying the name token; generic applications
become AST_TYPE_APPLICATION nodes whose value slot holds the
constructor-name token and whose children are the argument types in
declaration order; arrows become AST_TYPE_FUNCTION nodes with
[argument type, result type] children. Postfix application binds tighter
than the arrow (int option -> string is (int option) -> string) and
chains left-to-right (int option list is (int option) list), matching
the F# specification.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_type_atom" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse a named type, type variable, or prefix generic application

    Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser

    Let is_name be 0
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
        Set is_name to 1
    End If
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_TYPE_NAME from Lexer:
        Set is_name to 1
    End If

    If is_name is equal to 1:
        Let name_token be proc parse_dotted_name_token with parser

        Note: Prefix generic application List<int>, Dictionary<K, V>
        Let after_name be proc current_token_type with parser
        If after_name is equal to TOKEN_LESS_THAN from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser  Note: Skip <

            Let app_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_TYPE_APPLICATION
            proc set_node_value with app_node, name_token

            Let collecting be 1
            While collecting is equal to 1:
                Let arg_node be proc parse_type_expression with parser
                If arg_node is equal to 0:
                    Return 0
                End If
                proc add_child with app_node, arg_node

                Let sep_type be proc current_token_type with parser
                If sep_type is equal to TOKEN_COMMA from Lexer:
                    proc advance_token with parser  Note: Skip ,
                Otherwise:
                    Set collecting to 0
                End If
            End While

            Note: Close the angle bracket. Nested generics end with >> which
            Note: the lexer reads as the composition operator; splitting it in
            Note: place (rewriting the token's type tag to a single > without
            Note: advancing) lets the enclosing generic consume the second half.
            Let close_type be proc current_token_type with parser
            If close_type is equal to TOKEN_GREATER_THAN from Lexer:
                proc advance_token with parser
                Return app_node
            End If
            If close_type is equal to TOKEN_COMPOSE_RIGHT from Lexer:
                Let close_token be proc current_token with parser
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with close_token, 0, TOKEN_GREATER_THAN from Lexer
                Return app_node
            End If

            proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected '>' to close generic type application"
            Return 0
        End If

        Let type_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_TYPE_NAME
        proc set_node_value with type_node, name_token
        Return type_node
    End If

    Note: Parenthesised type (t)
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let inner be proc parse_type_expression with parser
        proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN from Lexer
        Return inner
    End If

    proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected type"
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "parse_type_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse type expression (names, generics, postfix applications, arrows)

    Let left be proc parse_type_atom with parser
    If left is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Postfix type-constructor applications: int option, int list,
    Note: 'a seq, int option list. Each juxtaposed name applies to the
    Note: entire type built so far, chaining left-to-right.
    Let postfixing be 1
    While postfixing is equal to 1:
        Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser
        Let is_ctor be 0
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
            Set is_ctor to 1
        End If
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_TYPE_NAME from Lexer:
            Set is_ctor to 1
        End If

        If is_ctor is equal to 0:
            Set postfixing to 0
            Continue
        End If

        Let ctor_token be proc parse_dotted_name_token with parser
        Let app_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_TYPE_APPLICATION
        proc set_node_value with app_node, ctor_token
        proc add_child with app_node, left
        Set left to app_node
    End While

    Set current_type to proc current_token_type with parser
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_ARROW from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let right be proc parse_type_expression with parser

        Let fn_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_TYPE_FUNCTION
        proc add_child with fn_node, left
        proc add_child with fn_node, right
        Return fn_node
    End If

    Return left
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: F# Pattern Collection Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Pattern context counterpart to parse_list_expression: same bracket-
and-semicolon syntax but elements are patterns rather than
expressions. AST_PATTERN_LIST identifies the pattern context.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_list_pattern" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse list pattern [x; y; z]

    proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET from Lexer

    Let list_pattern be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_PATTERN_LIST

    Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACKET from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return list_pattern
    End If

    Let collecting be 1
    While collecting is equal to 1:
        Let pattern be proc parse_pattern with parser
        If pattern is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        proc add_child with list_pattern, pattern

        Set current_type to proc current_token_type with parser
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_SEMICOLON from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Continue
        End If
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACKET from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Set collecting to 0
            Continue
        End If

        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected ';' or ']'"
        Return 0
    End While

    Return list_pattern
End Process

@Reasoning:
Array-pattern counterpart of parse_array_expression with
AST_PATTERN_ARRAY as the node kind.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_array_pattern" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse array pattern [|x; y; z|]

    proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_LEFT_ARRAY from Lexer

    Let array_pattern be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_PATTERN_ARRAY

    Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_RIGHT_ARRAY from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return array_pattern
    End If

    Let collecting be 1
    While collecting is equal to 1:
        Let pattern be proc parse_pattern with parser
        If pattern is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        proc add_child with array_pattern, pattern

        Set current_type to proc current_token_type with parser
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_SEMICOLON from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Continue
        End If
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_RIGHT_ARRAY from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Set collecting to 0
            Continue
        End If

        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected ';' or '|]'"
        Return 0
    End While

    Return array_pattern
End Process

@Reasoning:
Record patterns `{field = pat; field = pat}` destructure records. Each
field becomes an AST_PATTERN_VARIABLE node carrying the field-name
TOKEN in its value slot with the field's sub-pattern as its single
child - the exact contract translate_field_pattern in the HIR
translator reads.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_record_pattern" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse record pattern {field = pattern; ...}

    proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE from Lexer

    Let record_pattern be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_PATTERN_RECORD

    Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return record_pattern
    End If

    Let collecting be 1
    While collecting is equal to 1:
        Let field_type be proc current_token_type with parser
        If field_type is not equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
            proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected field name"
            Return 0
        End If
        Let field_token be proc current_token with parser
        proc advance_token with parser

        Let eq_ok be proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_EQUAL from Lexer
        If eq_ok is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        Let field_pattern be proc parse_pattern with parser

        Let field_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_PATTERN_VARIABLE
        proc set_node_value with field_node, field_token
        proc add_child with field_node, field_pattern
        proc add_child with record_pattern, field_node

        Set current_type to proc current_token_type with parser
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_SEMICOLON from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Continue
        End If
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Set collecting to 0
            Continue
        End If

        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected ';' or '}'"
        Return 0
    End While

    Return record_pattern
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: F# Declaration Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
A let-binding consists of an optional `rec` keyword, a name pattern,
zero or more curried parameter patterns, an optional `: returnType`
annotation, an `=`, and a body expression. The `rec` flag is stored in
the value slot using the TOKEN_REC type tag as a sentinel (heap token
pointers can never collide with the small constant). Function bindings
(parameters present) are desugared to name + AST_LAMBDA so the binding
node always has exactly two children [pattern, expression] - the HIR
translator's contract.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_let_binding" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse let binding (let [rec] name params... [: type] = expression)

    Let binding_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_LET_BINDING

    Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_REC from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        proc set_node_value with binding_node, TOKEN_REC from Lexer
    End If

    Note: Optional mutable modifier
    Set current_type to proc current_token_type with parser
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_MUTABLE from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Let pattern be proc parse_pattern with parser
    If pattern is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc add_child with binding_node, pattern

    Note: Collect curried function parameters until = or : or EOF
    Let params be proc list_create from List
    Let collecting be 1
    While collecting is equal to 1:
        Set current_type to proc current_token_type with parser

        Let is_param_start be 0
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
            Set is_param_start to 1
        End If
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_UNDERSCORE from Lexer:
            Set is_param_start to 1
        End If
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN from Lexer:
            Set is_param_start to 1
        End If

        If is_param_start is equal to 0:
            Set collecting to 0
            Continue
        End If

        Let param be proc parse_pattern with parser
        If param is equal to 0:
            Set collecting to 0
            Continue
        End If
        proc list_append from List with params, param
    End While

    Note: Optional return-type annotation
    Set current_type to proc current_token_type with parser
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_COLON from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let return_type be proc parse_type_expression with parser
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with binding_node, 40, return_type
    End If

    Let eq_ok be proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_EQUAL from Lexer
    If eq_ok is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc skip_newlines with parser

    Let expr be proc parse_expression with parser

    Note: Function bindings desugar to let name = fun params -> body
    Let param_count be proc list_length from List with params
    If param_count is greater than 0:
        Let lambda_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_LAMBDA
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than param_count:
            Let p be proc list_get from List with params, i
            proc add_child with lambda_node, p
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        proc add_child with lambda_node, expr
        proc add_child with binding_node, lambda_node
    Otherwise:
        proc add_child with binding_node, expr
    End If

    Return binding_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
F# type declarations have four special kinds (record, discriminated
union, class, interface) plus the type-abbreviation form, all
introduced by `type Name = ...`. The token after `=` disambiguates:
`{` record, `|` union (or a TYPE_NAME whose successor is `|` or `of`
for unions without the leading pipe), `class`, `interface`, anything
else an abbreviation.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_type_declaration" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse type declaration

    proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_TYPE from Lexer

    Let type_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_TYPE_DECLARATION

    Let name_type be proc current_token_type with parser
    Let is_name be 0
    If name_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
        Set is_name to 1
    End If
    If name_type is equal to TOKEN_TYPE_NAME from Lexer:
        Set is_name to 1
    End If
    If is_name is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected type name"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let name_token be proc current_token with parser
    proc set_node_value with type_node, name_token
    proc advance_token with parser

    Let eq_ok be proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_EQUAL from Lexer
    If eq_ok is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc skip_newlines with parser

    Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser

    Note: Record type {field: type; ...}
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE from Lexer:
        Let record_type be proc parse_record_type with parser
        proc add_child with type_node, record_type
        Return type_node
    End If

    Note: Union type | Case1 | Case2 of type
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_PIPE from Lexer:
        Let union_type be proc parse_union_type with parser
        proc add_child with type_node, union_type
        Return type_node
    End If

    Note: Union without leading pipe: type T = A | B of int
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_TYPE_NAME from Lexer:
        Let after_type be proc peek_token_type with parser, 1
        Let is_union be 0
        If after_type is equal to TOKEN_PIPE from Lexer:
            Set is_union to 1
        End If
        If after_type is equal to TOKEN_OF from Lexer:
            Set is_union to 1
        End If
        If is_union is equal to 1:
            Set union_type to proc parse_union_type with parser
            proc add_child with type_node, union_type
            Return type_node
        End If
    End If

    Note: Class type
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_CLASS from Lexer:
        Let class_type be proc parse_class_type with parser
        proc add_child with type_node, class_type
        Return type_node
    End If

    Note: Interface type
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_INTERFACE from Lexer:
        Let interface_type be proc parse_interface_type with parser
        proc add_child with type_node, interface_type
        Return type_node
    End If

    Note: Type abbreviation (type alias)
    Let type_expr be proc parse_type_expression with parser
    proc add_child with type_node, type_expr

    Return type_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Record type declarations look like `{field: type; field: type}`,
distinguished from record values by the colon. Field declarations are
stored as AST_VALUE_DECLARATION children (value slot = field-name
token, single child = field type) - the contract translate_type_body
reads when building HIR field definitions.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_record_type" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse record type {field: type; ...}

    proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE from Lexer
    proc skip_newlines with parser

    Let record_type be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_RECORD_TYPE

    Let collecting be 1
    While collecting is equal to 1:
        proc skip_newlines with parser
        Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Set collecting to 0
            Continue
        End If

        Let field_type_tag be proc current_token_type with parser
        If field_type_tag is not equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
            proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected field name"
            Return 0
        End If
        Let field_token be proc current_token with parser
        proc advance_token with parser

        Let colon_ok be proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_COLON from Lexer
        If colon_ok is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        Let field_type be proc parse_type_expression with parser

        Let field_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_VALUE_DECLARATION
        proc set_node_value with field_node, field_token
        proc add_child with field_node, field_type
        proc add_child with record_type, field_node

        proc skip_newlines with parser
        Set current_type to proc current_token_type with parser
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_SEMICOLON from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Continue
        End If
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Set collecting to 0
            Continue
        End If

        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected ';' or '}'"
        Return 0
    End While

    Return record_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
F# discriminated unions use `| Case1 | Case2 of type` syntax. Each
case becomes an AST_TYPE_NAME node holding the constructor-name token
as its value, with the optional payload type as a child when `of` is
present. Newlines between cases are insignificant.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_union_type" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse discriminated union type | Case1 | Case2 of type

    Let union_type be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_UNION_TYPE

    Let collecting be 1
    While collecting is equal to 1:
        proc skip_newlines with parser
        Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_PIPE from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
        End If

        Let case_type be proc current_token_type with parser
        If case_type is not equal to TOKEN_TYPE_NAME from Lexer:
            proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected case name"
            Return 0
        End If
        Let case_token be proc current_token with parser
        proc advance_token with parser

        Let case_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_TYPE_NAME
        proc set_node_value with case_node, case_token

        Set current_type to proc current_token_type with parser
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_OF from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Let payload_type be proc parse_type_expression with parser
            proc add_child with case_node, payload_type
        End If

        proc add_child with union_type, case_node

        proc skip_newlines with parser
        Set current_type to proc current_token_type with parser
        If current_type is not equal to TOKEN_PIPE from Lexer:
            Set collecting to 0
        End If
    End While

    Return union_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
F# class types are bracketed with `class ... end` after the `=` of
their type declaration. Body members come in three flavors (member
methods, val properties, let bindings) handled by parse_class_member.
Unrecognized tokens at member position are skipped via a one-token
advance to keep parsing progressing.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_class_type" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse class type declaration

    proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_CLASS from Lexer
    proc skip_newlines with parser

    Let class_type be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_CLASS_TYPE

    Let collecting be 1
    While collecting is equal to 1:
        proc skip_newlines with parser
        Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_END from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Set collecting to 0
            Continue
        End If
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
            Set collecting to 0
            Continue
        End If

        Let member be proc parse_class_member with parser
        If member is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with class_type, member
        Otherwise:
            proc advance_token with parser  Note: Skip unknown token
        End If
    End While

    Return class_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
Interface types use `interface ... end` containing abstract member
declarations and val-property signatures only (no concrete bindings,
since interfaces have no implementations).
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_interface_type" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse interface type declaration

    proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_INTERFACE from Lexer
    proc skip_newlines with parser

    Let interface_type be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_INTERFACE_TYPE

    Let collecting be 1
    While collecting is equal to 1:
        proc skip_newlines with parser
        Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_END from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Set collecting to 0
            Continue
        End If
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
            Set collecting to 0
            Continue
        End If

        Let member be proc parse_interface_member with parser
        If member is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with interface_type, member
        Otherwise:
            proc advance_token with parser  Note: Skip unknown token
        End If
    End While

    Return interface_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
Three class-member kinds dispatch by leading keyword: `member`
introduces a method, `val` a property, `let` a field or private
method. Anything else is a parse error at member position (the caller
recovers by skipping one token).
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_class_member" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse class member (method, property, field)

    Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser

    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_MEMBER from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return proc parse_method_declaration with parser
    End If

    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_VAL from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_property_declaration with parser
    End If

    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_LET from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return proc parse_let_binding with parser
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Interface members are restricted to abstract method signatures
(`abstract` keyword) and val-property signatures.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_interface_member" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse interface member (abstract method or property)

    Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser

    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_ABSTRACT from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return proc parse_method_declaration with parser
    End If

    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_VAL from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_property_declaration with parser
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Method declarations take the shape `[this.]name [(params)] [: type]`.
The F# member self-identifier (`member this.Method`) is recognised and
the method name is the token after the dot. Each parameter is parsed
as a full pattern so destructuring parameters work. Parameters and the
optional return type are stored as children, return type last.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_method_declaration" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse method declaration

    Let method_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_METHOD_DECLARATION

    Let name_type be proc current_token_type with parser
    If name_type is not equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected method name"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: member this.Name - skip the self identifier
    Let after_type be proc peek_token_type with parser, 1
    If after_type is equal to TOKEN_DOT from Lexer:
        Let dotted_type be proc peek_token_type with parser, 2
        If dotted_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser  Note: skip self identifier
            proc advance_token with parser  Note: skip dot
        End If
    End If

    Let name_token be proc current_token with parser
    proc set_node_value with method_node, name_token
    proc advance_token with parser

    Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser

        Let collecting be 1
        While collecting is equal to 1:
            Set current_type to proc current_token_type with parser
            If current_type is equal to TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN from Lexer:
                proc advance_token with parser
                Set collecting to 0
                Continue
            End If
            If current_type is equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
                Set collecting to 0
                Continue
            End If

            Let param be proc parse_pattern with parser
            If param is equal to 0:
                Set collecting to 0
                Continue
            End If

            Note: Optional parameter type annotation
            Set current_type to proc current_token_type with parser
            If current_type is equal to TOKEN_COLON from Lexer:
                proc advance_token with parser
                Let param_type be proc parse_type_expression with parser
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with param, 40, param_type
            End If

            proc add_child with method_node, param

            Set current_type to proc current_token_type with parser
            If current_type is equal to TOKEN_COMMA from Lexer:
                proc advance_token with parser
            End If
        End While
    End If

    Set current_type to proc current_token_type with parser
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_COLON from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let return_type be proc parse_type_expression with parser
        proc add_child with method_node, return_type
    End If

    Return method_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Property declarations use `val name: Type` syntax; both the identifier
and the type annotation are mandatory.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_property_declaration" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse property declaration

    proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_VAL from Lexer

    Let property_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_PROPERTY_DECLARATION

    Let name_type be proc current_token_type with parser
    If name_type is not equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected property name"
        Return 0
    End If
    Let name_token be proc current_token with parser
    proc set_node_value with property_node, name_token
    proc advance_token with parser

    Let colon_ok be proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_COLON from Lexer
    If colon_ok is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let property_type be proc parse_type_expression with parser
    proc add_child with property_node, property_type

    Return property_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Top-level value declarations also use `val name: Type` syntax but
produce AST_VALUE_DECLARATION so semantic analysis can tell
module-level signatures apart from type-body properties.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_value_declaration" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse value declaration

    proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_VAL from Lexer

    Let value_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_VALUE_DECLARATION

    Let name_type be proc current_token_type with parser
    If name_type is not equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected value name"
        Return 0
    End If
    Let name_token be proc current_token with parser
    proc set_node_value with value_node, name_token
    proc advance_token with parser

    Let colon_ok be proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_COLON from Lexer
    If colon_ok is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let value_type be proc parse_type_expression with parser
    proc add_child with value_node, value_type

    Return value_node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Module-Level Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
F# modules group declarations under a common name. The `= ` form
(`module Name = ...`) and the top-level form (`module Name` with no
equals) are both accepted. The body is parsed as a sequence of
declarations until EOF or a declaration that fails without raising a
hard error (the boundary of this parser's layout sensitivity).
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_module_declaration" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse module declaration

    proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_MODULE from Lexer

    Let module_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_MODULE

    Let name_type be proc current_token_type with parser
    Let is_name be 0
    If name_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
        Set is_name to 1
    End If
    If name_type is equal to TOKEN_TYPE_NAME from Lexer:
        Set is_name to 1
    End If
    If is_name is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected module name"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let name_token be proc parse_dotted_name_token with parser
    proc set_node_value with module_node, name_token

    Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_EQUAL from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Let parsing be 1
    While parsing is equal to 1:
        proc skip_newlines with parser
        Set current_type to proc current_token_type with parser
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
            Set parsing to 0
            Continue
        End If
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_DOUBLE_SEMICOLON from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Continue
        End If

        Let declaration be proc parse_declaration with parser
        If declaration is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with module_node, declaration
        Otherwise:
            Set parsing to 0
        End If
    End While

    Return module_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Namespaces partition declarations by dotted path. This parser is
permissive (semantic analysis enforces the no-values restriction
later); the body loop matches parse_module_declaration.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_namespace_declaration" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse namespace declaration

    proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_NAMESPACE from Lexer

    Let namespace_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_NAMESPACE

    Let name_type be proc current_token_type with parser
    Let is_name be 0
    If name_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
        Set is_name to 1
    End If
    If name_type is equal to TOKEN_TYPE_NAME from Lexer:
        Set is_name to 1
    End If
    If is_name is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected namespace name"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let name_token be proc parse_dotted_name_token with parser
    proc set_node_value with namespace_node, name_token

    Let parsing be 1
    While parsing is equal to 1:
        proc skip_newlines with parser
        Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
            Set parsing to 0
            Continue
        End If

        Let declaration be proc parse_declaration with parser
        If declaration is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with namespace_node, declaration
        Otherwise:
            Set parsing to 0
        End If
    End While

    Return namespace_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
`open Module.Path` brings a module or namespace's names into scope.
The full dotted path is joined into a single name token stored as the
node value so the HIR translator emits one import directive.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_open_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse open statement

    proc consume_token with parser, TOKEN_OPEN from Lexer

    Let open_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_OPEN

    Let name_type be proc current_token_type with parser
    Let is_name be 0
    If name_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
        Set is_name to 1
    End If
    If name_type is equal to TOKEN_TYPE_NAME from Lexer:
        Set is_name to 1
    End If
    If is_name is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected module path"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let name_token be proc parse_dotted_name_token with parser
    proc set_node_value with open_node, name_token

    Return open_node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: F# Program Structure Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level declaration dispatcher. Selects between module, namespace,
open, type, let-binding, val-declaration, and do-/expression-
statements based on the leading token. Top-level expressions (common
in scripts: `printfn "hi"`) are wrapped in an AST_LET_BINDING with a
wildcard pattern so the module body remains a uniform list of binding
shapes for the HIR translator.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_declaration" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse top-level declaration

    Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser

    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_MODULE from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_module_declaration with parser
    End If

    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_NAMESPACE from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_namespace_declaration with parser
    End If

    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_OPEN from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_open_statement with parser
    End If

    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_TYPE from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_type_declaration with parser
    End If

    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_LET from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return proc parse_let_binding with parser
    End If

    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_VAL from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_value_declaration with parser
    End If

    Note: do-binding: `do expr` evaluates an expression for effects
    If current_type is equal to TOKEN_DO from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        proc skip_newlines with parser
        Let do_expr be proc parse_expression with parser
        If do_expr is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Let do_binding be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_LET_BINDING
        Let do_pattern be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_PATTERN_WILDCARD
        proc add_child with do_binding, do_pattern
        proc add_child with do_binding, do_expr
        Return do_binding
    End If

    Note: Bare top-level expression statement
    Let can_expr be proc is_primary_start with parser
    If can_expr is equal to 1:
        Let stmt_expr be proc parse_expression with parser
        If stmt_expr is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Let stmt_binding be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_LET_BINDING
        Let stmt_pattern be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_PATTERN_WILDCARD
        proc add_child with stmt_binding, stmt_pattern
        proc add_child with stmt_binding, stmt_expr
        Return stmt_binding
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
The program-level loop must tolerate intervening trivia (newlines, ;;
separators, # directives) because F# allows them between declarations.
Recovery on a failing declaration: a hard parse error propagates (the
partial tree would be misleading), while an unrecognized token is
skipped so unknown noise cannot deadlock the parser.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_program" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse complete F# program

    Let program_node be proc create_ast_node with parser, AST_PROGRAM

    Let parsing be 1
    While parsing is equal to 1:
        Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
            Set parsing to 0
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Skip trivia between declarations
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_NEWLINE from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Continue
        End If
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_DOUBLE_SEMICOLON from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Hash directives (#light, #nowarn) - skip to end of line
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_HASH from Lexer:
            Let skipping be 1
            While skipping is equal to 1:
                Let t be proc current_token_type with parser
                If t is equal to TOKEN_NEWLINE from Lexer:
                    Set skipping to 0
                    Continue
                End If
                If t is equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
                    Set skipping to 0
                    Continue
                End If
                proc advance_token with parser
            End While
            Continue
        End If

        Let declaration be proc parse_declaration with parser
        If declaration is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with program_node, declaration
        Otherwise:
            Let has_error be proc has_parse_error with parser
            If has_error is equal to 1:
                Return 0
            End If
            proc advance_token with parser  Note: Skip unknown token
        End If
    End While

    Return program_node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Main F# Parsing Entry Point
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Sole public entry point. Couples parser construction, the parse_program
walk, and post-parse error checking. On error the parser AND its arena
are destroyed (no partially-constructed tree escapes). On success the
parser record is released but the arena deliberately survives: it owns
every AST node in the returned tree, and the HIR translator reads that
tree after this function returns. The arena's ownership transfers to
the AST consumer.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_fsharp_source" takes token_list as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Main entry point for parsing F# source code

    Let parser be proc create_fsharp_parser with token_list
    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let ast_root be proc parse_program with parser

    Let has_error be proc has_parse_error with parser
    If has_error is equal to 1:
        proc destroy_fsharp_parser with parser
        Return 0
    End If

    If ast_root is equal to 0:
        proc destroy_fsharp_parser with parser
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Success: release the parser record but keep the arena alive -
    Note: it owns the AST nodes the caller is about to consume
    proc deallocate from Layout with parser
    Return ast_root
End Process

Note: End of F# Parser
